{
  "doc_id": "41703",
  "text": "As the circadian clock is involved in the regulation of numerous biological processes, it is of no surprise, that its deregulations are associated with many different types of diseases. These include sleeping disorders (familial advanced sleep-phase syndrome (FASPS), sleep problems in the elderly) [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] , neuropsychiatric disturbances (seasonal affective disorder (SAD), bipolar disorders) [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] , metabolic diseases (diabetes and obesity) [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] , cardiovascular disorders [CITATION_7] and cancer development [CITATION_8] . Additionally, weak response to anticancer treatments was reported in cancer patients with disturbed circadian rhythms, as compared to the ones with normal circadian phenotype [CITATION_9] .",
